04512nam a22005775i 9780822387459DE-B159720220302035458.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220302t20032005ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808223874597 a10.1515/97808223874592doi  a(DE-B1597)554340  a(OCoLC)1157924052  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC 4aD767.92b.R67 2003 7aHIS0271002bisacsh04a940.54262221 aRosenberg, Emily S., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut12aA Date Which Will Live :bPearl Harbor in American Memory /cEmily S. Rosenberg; ed. by Gilbert M. Joseph. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[2003] 4c©2005  a1 online resource (247 p.) :b15 b&w photos  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aAmerican encounters/global interactions : 3900tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- tI Signifying Pearl Harbor -- t1. Infamy -- t2. Backdoor Deceit -- t3. Representations of Race and Japanese-American Relations -- t4. Commemoration of Sacrifice -- tII Reviving Pearl Harbor after 1991 -- t5. Bilateral Relations -- t6. The Memory Boom and the ‘‘Greatest Generation’’ -- t7. The Kimmel Crusade, the History Wars, and the Republican Revival -- t8. Japanese Americans -- t9. Spectacular History -- t10 Day of Infamy -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aDecember 7, 1941—the date of Japan’s surprise attack on the U.S. fleet at Pearl Harbor—is "a date which will live" in American history and memory, but the stories that will live and the meanings attributed to them are hardly settled. In movies, books, and magazines, at memorial sites and public ceremonies, and on television and the internet, Pearl Harbor lives in a thousand guises and symbolizes dozens of different historical lessons. In A Date Which Will Live, historian Emily S. Rosenberg examines the contested meanings of Pearl Harbor in American culture.Rosenberg considers the emergence of Pearl Harbor’s symbolic role within multiple contexts: as a day of infamy that highlighted the need for future U.S. military preparedness, as an attack that opened a "back door" to U.S. involvement in World War II, as an event of national commemoration, and as a central metaphor in American-Japanese relations. She explores the cultural background that contributed to Pearl Harbor’s resurgence in American memory after the fiftieth anniversary of the attack in 1991. In doing so, she discusses the recent “memory boom” in American culture; the movement to exonerate the military commanders at Pearl Harbor, Admiral Husband Kimmel and General Walter Short; the political mobilization of various groups during the culture and history "wars" of the 1990s, and the spectacle surrounding the movie Pearl Harbor. Rosenberg concludes with a look at the uses of Pearl Harbor as a historical frame for understanding the events of September 11, 2001.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aPearl Harbor (Hawaii), Attack on, 1941. 0aPopular culturezUnited States. 0aWorld War, 1939-1945xInfluence. 7aHISTORY / Military / World War II.2bisacsh1 aJoseph, Gilbert M., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDuke University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311071183740uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780822387459zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780822387459423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780822387459/original  a978-3-11-071183-7  Duke University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_DUK_ALL  aEBA_DUK_EALL  aEBA_DUK_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles